      "id": 7,
      "options": {
        "content": "Slow trace workflow:\n\n1. Start from the Service Overview or Worker Overview dashboard.\n2. Identify the time window and service with elevated latency.\n3. Open Grafana Explore with the Tempo datasource.\n4. Search for traces in the same time window, filtered by service, and sort by duration.\n5. Open an individual trace and use the provisioned trace-to-logs pivot to inspect matching Loki records.\n\nRecommended Tempo search filters:\n\n- API latency: `service.name = \\\"<service>\\\"`\n- Worker failures: `service.name = \\\"<service>\\\" && status = error`\n- Duration drilldown: add a duration threshold in Explore when searching.",
        "mode": "markdown"
      },
      "title": "Slow Trace Drilldown Workflow",
      "type": "text"
    },
    {
      "gridPos": {
        "h": 9,
        "w": 12,
        "x": 12,
        "y": 31
      },
      "id": 8,
      "options": {
        "content": "Trace and worker failure workflow:\n\n1. If you already have a `trace_id`, set the dashboard variable and inspect the `Logs by Trace ID` panel.\n2. If the log line includes `trace_id`, use Loki derived fields to jump into Tempo.\n3. From the Tempo trace view, use the configured trace-to-logs correlation to jump back into Loki.\n4. For worker failures, filter logs by worker service and `level=error`, then use `job_name`, `job.status`, and `trace_id` fields to isolate the failing execution.\n\nThis dashboard intentionally relies on Grafana Explore for the actual Tempo search UI because that workflow is more stable than embedding brittle trace-search panels in JSON.",
        "mode": "markdown"
      },
      "title": "Trace And Log Correlation Workflow",
      "type": "text"
    }
